    cout << get_string() << endl; // Output: Hello world! modified

    return 0;
}
```
On the other hand, "passing by value" (or simply "by val") means that a function is receiving a copy of the data passed to it rather than a reference to the data. This means that any changes made to the data inside the function are not reflected back to the caller. For example:
```c++
void modify_string(std::string& str) {
